'''Bronwyn Bancroft''' (born 1958) is an [[Indigenous Australians|Indigenous Australian]] artist, notable for being the first Australian fashion designer invited to show her work in Paris. Born in [[Tenterfield, New South Wales]], and trained in [[Canberra]] and [[Sydney]], Bancroft worked as a fashion designer, and is an artist, illustrator, and arts administrator. 

In 1985 Bancroft established a shop called Designer Aboriginals, selling fabrics made by Indigenous artists including herself. She was a founding member of Boomalli Aboriginal Artists Co-operative. Art work by Bancroft is held by the [[National Gallery of Australia]], the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] and the [[Art Gallery of Western Australia]]. She has provided art work for over 20&nbsp;children's books, including ''Stradbroke Dreaming'' by writer and activist [[Oodgeroo Noonuccal]] and books by artist and writer [[Sally Morgan (artist)|Sally Morgan]]. She has also received design commissions, including one for the exterior of a sports centre in Sydney.

With a long history of involvement in community activism and arts administration, Bancroft has served as a board member for the National Gallery of Australia. Her painting ''Prevention of AIDS'' (1992) was used in a campaign to raise awareness of [[HIV/AIDS]] in Australia. As of 2010, Bancroft sits on the boards of copyright collection agency Viscopy and Tranby Aboriginal College, as well as being on the Artists Board at the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Sydney]].

==Life and training==
A [[Bundjalung people|Bundjalung]] woman,<ref name="NMApanel">{{cite web|url=http://www.nma.gov.au/audio/transcripts/NMA_urban1_20070706.html|title=Panel 1: Who you callin' urban?|last=Aird|first=Michael|coauthors=Richard Bell, Vernon Ah Kee, Bronwyn Bancroft, Anita Heiss and Wesley Enoch|date=6 July 2007|work=Who You Callin<U+2019> Urban? forum|publisher=National Museum of Australia|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref><ref name="Watson"/> Bancroft was born in [[Tenterfield, New South Wales|Tenterfield]], a town in rural [[New South Wales]] in 1958.<ref name="BancroftAWR">{{cite web|url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/biogs/AWE0981b.htm|title=Bancroft, Bronwyn (1958 <U+2013> )|last=Kovacic|first=Leonarda|date=2004|work=The Australian Women's Register|publisher= National Foundation for Australian Women and University of Melbourne|accessdate=8 October 2009}}</ref> She was the youngest of seven children of Owen Cecil Joseph Bancroft, known as "Bill"<U+2014>an Indigenous Australian from the Djanbun clan<U+2014>and Dot, who was of [[Scottish people|Scottish]]<U+2013>[[Polish Australian|Polish]] ancestry.<ref name="Strokes">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/tv/messagestick/stories/s1051118.htm|title=Strokes of colour|date=27 February 2004|work=Message Stick|publisher=ABC TV|accessdate=17 February 2010}}</ref><ref name="Boomallibio">{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080719015018/boomalli.org.au/index.php?view=article&catid=35:founding-members&id=55:bronwyn-bancroft&option=com_content&Itemid=62|title=Founding members: Bronwyn Bancroft|publisher=Boomalli Aboriginal Artists' Cooperative|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref> Bancroft has stated that her great-great-great-grandmother Pemau was one of only two or three survivors from her clan, the rest murdered when their land was settled by a white farmer.<ref name="NMApanel"/> She recalled that her father's education was obstructed by discrimination because he was aboriginal. His lack of formal training meant that he had to work away from home as a [[Railroad tie|sleeper]]-cutter while Bancroft's mother worked at home as a dressmaker.<ref name="Strokes"/> Bancroft's father worked as an engineer during World War II, managing barges at [[Madang]] and [[Rabaul]].<ref name="NMApanel"/>

With her father emphasising the importance of getting an education or a trade, Bancroft completed high school in Tenterfield before moving to [[Canberra]] in 1976 with her husband-to-be Ned Menning, who had also been her teacher.<ref name="NMApanel"/> There Bancroft completed a Diploma of Visual Communications through the Canberra School of Art, followed by a Master of Studio Practice and a Master of Visual Arts (Paintings) at the [[University of Sydney]].<ref name="McCulloch"/> She never returned to live in Tenterfield,<ref name="NMApanel"/> although her three sisters were living there in 2004. Bancroft has three children: Jack was born in 1985, Ella in 1988, and Rubyrose in 2000.<ref name="Strokes"/>

==Art and design==
Bancroft was a founding member of the Boomalli Aboriginal Artists Co-operative,<ref name="Watson"/> one of Australia's oldest Indigenous-run artists' organisations,<ref name="AboutBoomalli">{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080718170042/boomalli.org.au/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=45&Itemid=61|title=About Boomalli|publisher=Boomalli Aboriginal Artists' Cooperative|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref> established in 1987.<ref name="LH95">{{cite journal|last=McGrath|first=Ann|date=1995|title=Boomalli Aboriginal Artists Co-operative. Interview with Hetti Perkins and Brenda Croft|journal=Labour History|volume=69|pages=217<U+2013>230}}</ref> She served in the roles of chairperson, director, and treasurer during its first two decades.<ref name="Boomallibio"/><ref name="NMApanel"/> In 1985 she opened a shop in Sydney called Designer Aboriginals, selling the work of Indigenous designers including her own fabrics,<ref name="Watson"/> and staffed by her Indigenous female students.<ref name="McCulloch">{{cite book|last=McCulloch|first=Alan|coauthors=Susan McCulloch, Emily McCulloch Childs|title=The new McCulloch's encyclopedia of Australian art|page=34|publisher=Aus Art Editions in association with The Miegunyah Press|location=Fitzroy, VIC|date=2006|isbn=052285317X}}</ref> Exhibiting at the 1987 Printemps Fashion Parade,<ref name="EAA">{{cite book|last=De Brabander|first=Dallas|title=[[Encyclopaedia of Aboriginal Australia]]|editor=David Horton|publisher=Aboriginal Studies Press for the Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies|location=Canberra|date=1994|volume=1|page=90|chapter=Bancroft, B.|isbn=9780855752347}}</ref> she was the first Australian fashion designer invited to show her work<U+2014>painted designs on cloth<U+2014>in Paris.<ref name="FiveKooriArtists">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/aplacetothink/html/boomalli.htm|title=Boomalli: Five Koori Artists|last=Humfress|first=Paul|coauthors=Michael Riley, Loretta Fisher|date=1988|work=A Place to Think|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=8 October 2009}}</ref> Two years later, in 1989, she contributed to a London exhibition, ''Australian Fashion: The Contemporary Art''.<ref name="EAA"/> Despite these successes she moved away from the fashion industry, telling an interviewer in 2005 that she had not done fabric design for fifteen years.<ref name="Sweeney"/> Described as "an instinctive colourist", Bancroft has since worked primarily as a painter, and has developed "a glowing style reminiscent of stained glass windows".<ref name="Watson"/> She has cited as influences the American painter [[Georgia O'Keeffe]], European painters [[Joan Mir<U+00F3>]],<ref name="Watson">{{cite book|last=Watson|first=Ken|title=The Oxford Companion to Aboriginal art and culture|editor=Sylvia Kleinert and Margot Neale|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|date=2000|pages=532<U+2013>533|chapter=Bancroft, Bronwyn|ISBN=0195506499}}</ref> [[Wassily Kandinsky]], and [[Marc Chagall]], and Australian Indigenous artists such as [[Emily Kngwarreye]], [[Rover Thomas]], and Mary MacLean.<ref name="Rawlins">{{cite journal|last=Rawlins|first=Donna|date=1996|title=Know the illustrator: Bronwyn Bancroft|journal=Magpies|volume=11|issue=2|pages=4<U+2013>7}}</ref>

While initially known as a fabric and textile designer, Bancroft has worked with many artistic media, including "jewellery design, painting, collage, illustration, sculpture and interior decoration".<ref name="McCulloch"/> Art works by Bancroft are held by the National Gallery of Australia, the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]], the [[Art Gallery of Western Australia]] and the [[Queensland Art Gallery]].<ref name="McCulloch"/> The National Gallery holds one of her screenprints, ''Entrapped'', created in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artsearch.nga.gov.au/Detail.cfm?IRN=121601|title=Entrapped|last=Bancroft|first=Bronwyn|work=Australasian Art Collection|publisher=National Gallery of Australia|accessdate=8 October 2009}}</ref> Between 1989 and 2006 Bancroft held 8&nbsp;solo exhibitions and participated in at least 53&nbsp;group exhibitions, including shows at the [[Australian Museum]] in Sydney, the National Gallery of Australia and the National Gallery of Victoria.<ref name="McCulloch"/>

In 2004 Bancroft was commissioned to design a large mural covering the exterior of a sports centre housing two basketball courts at Tempe Reserve in [[Marrickville, New South Wales]]. The mural depicts a snake, a man, and a woman, representing both biblical and Indigenous Australian creation stories. It also includes the [[goanna]], ancestral totem of the Marrickville area's original inhabitants, the [[Wangal people]].<ref name="Sweeney">{{cite journal|last=Sweeney|first=Therese|date=Dec<U+2013>Jan 2005|title=A cultural gateway|journal=Real Time Arts Magazine|issue=70|pages=54|url=http://www.realtimearts.net/article/70/8009}}</ref>

In 1993 Bancroft first ventured into illustrating children's books, providing the artwork for ''Fat and Juicy Place'' written by Dianna Kidd. The book was shortlisted for the [[Children's Book Council of Australia]]'s Book of the Year and won the Australian Multicultural Children's Book Award.<ref name="bookillus">{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080718234944/www.bronwynbancroft.com/5.html|title=Book illustrations|last=Bancroft|first=Bronwyn|work=Designer Aboriginals|accessdate=13 November 2009}}</ref> In the same year, she illustrated ''Stradbroke Dreamtime'' by Indigenous activist and writer [[Oodgeroo Noonuccal]]. She was the third artist to have provided images for successive editions of the book, the first edition of which had been released in 1972.<ref name="O'Conor">{{cite book|last=O'Conor|first=Juliet|title=Bottersnikes and other lost things : a celebration of Australian illustrated children's books|publisher=Miegunyah Press and State Library of Victoria|location=Carlton, Vic.|date=2009|page=124|isbn=9780522856514}}</ref> Bancroft has since contributed artwork for over 20&nbsp;children's books, including some by prominent Australian writer and artist [[Sally Morgan (artist)|Sally Morgan]], whom she regards as a mentor and friend.<ref name="Sweeney"/> These have included ''Dan's grandpa'' (1996)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fremantlepress.com.au/books/788|title=Books: Dan's Grandpa|publisher=Freemantle Press|accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref> and ''Sam's bush journey'' (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.cat-vn4470368 |title=Sam's bush journey|last=Morgan|first=Sally|coauthors=Ezekiel Kwaymullina, Bronwyn Bancroft|date=2009|publisher=National Library of Australia catalogue|accessdate=9 October 2009}}</ref> The two artists also collaborated on an exhibition of prints at [[Warrnambool]] Art Gallery in Victoria in 1991.<ref name="EAA"/> Researcher and museum curator Margo Neale has described the art of both Bancroft and Morgan as depicting "their relationship to country and family in generally high-keyed works, celebrating and commemorating through personal or collective stories in mainly figurative narratives."<ref name="Urban">{{cite book|last=Neale|first=Margo|title=The Oxford Companion to Aboriginal art and culture|editor=Sylvia Kleinert and Margot Neale|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|date=2000|pages=267-278|chapter=United in the struggle: Indigenous art from urban areas|ISBN=0195506499}}</ref>

As well as working with established writers, Bancroft has created a number of children's books in her own right, including ''An Australian 1 2 3 of Animals'' and ''An Australian ABC of Animals'', which have been favourably reviewed as imaginative and well-illustrated.<ref name="Coughlan">{{cite web|url=http://www.papertigers.org/reviews/USA/papertigers/AnAustralian123OfAnimalsANDAnAustralianABCOfAnimals.html|last=Coughlan|first=Marjorie|date=October 2009|title=Review: An Australian 123 Of Animals, and An Australian ABC Of Animals |work=PaperTigers|accessdate=12 November 2009}}</ref> The style of illustration was described as "traditional Australian Aboriginal representation rendered in bright, eye-catching colors."<ref name="Coughlan"/> In addition to illustrating children's books, Bancroft's art has been used by a number of other individuals and organisations, including as cover art for publications from the Australian Museum<ref>{{cite book|last=Kelly|first=Lynda|coauthors=Allison Bartlett and Phil Gordon|title=Indigenous Youth and Museums|publisher=Australian Museum|location=Sydney|date=2002|isbn=0 7347 2312 1|url=http://australianmuseum.net.au/Uploads/Documents/2588/iym_full_report.pdf|accessdate=10 December 2009}}</ref> and the New South Wales Education Department,<ref>{{cite book|last=NSW Department of Education and Training|title=Talking identity: teacher<U+2019>s handbook|publisher=NSW Department of Education and Training|location=Ryde, NSW|date=2002|isbn=0 7313 7088 0|url=http://www.curriculumsupport.education.nsw.gov.au/primary/hsie/assets/pdf/talkingidentity.pdf|accessdate=10 December 2009}}</ref> for [[Larissa Behrendt]]'s novel ''Home'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Behrendt|first=Larissa|title=Home|publisher=University of Queensland Press|location=St Lucia, QLD|date=2004|isbn=9780702234071}}</ref> and for [[Roberta Sykes]]'s controversial autobiographical narratives ''Snake Cradle'' and ''Snake Dancing''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kurtzer|first=Sonja|date=2001|title=Beryl Henderson Prize-winning Essay: Identity Dilemmas in Roberta Sykes' Autobiographical Narratives, Snake Cradle and Snake Dancing|journal=Australian Feminist Studies|volume=16|issue=34|pages=101<U+2013>111}}</ref>

==Administration and activism==
Bancroft has been active in arts organisations, and served two terms on the board of the National Gallery of Australia during the 1990s. She was chair of the Visual Arts Board of the New South Wales Ministry for the Arts,<ref name="Rawlins"/> and of the National Indigenous Arts Advocacy Organisation from 1993 to 1996.<ref name="Watson"/> In the lead-up to the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] in Sydney, Bancroft was a member of the design committee that provided advice on the development of the games' official logo.<ref>{{cite book|last=Meekison|first=Lisa|title=Indigenous cultures in an interconnected world|editor=Claire Smith and Graeme Ward|publisher=UBC Press|location=Vancouver|date=2000|page=116|chapter=Indigenous presence in the Sydney Games|isbn=0774808063}}</ref> She has acted as a judge for the $35,000 Country Energy Art Prize.<ref>{{cite journal|date=2007|title=Broadened focus for 5th $35,000 Country Energy Art Prize|journal=Australian Artist|volume=24|issue=2|pages=7}}</ref> Bancroft is a member of the [[board of directors]] of the Australian [[List of copyright collection societies|copyright collection agency]], Viscopy, and has been an advocate for [[Droit de suite|resale royalty rights]] for artists while serving in the position.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Paul|date=2003|title=The Resale Royalty and Australian Visual Artists: Painting the Full Picture|journal=Media & Arts Law Review|volume=8|pages=306|url=http://www.law.unimelb.edu.au/CMCL/malr/8-4-3%20Lewis%20Article%20Formatted%20for%20web.pdf|accessdate=10 December 2009}}</ref> She has observed that "resale royalties are an intrinsic link to the improvement of the inherent rights of Australian artists to a fair income".<ref>{{cite journal|date=2002|title=Government to Consider Resale Royalty Right for Artists|journal=Off the Air|publisher=Screenrights|volume=11|issue=3|pages=15}}</ref> She was a member of the Sydney Museum of Contemporary Art's Artist Advisory Group in 2005,<ref>{{cite book|last=Museum of Contemporary Art, Sydney|title=Annual Report|publisher=Museum of Contemporary Art, Sydney|location=Sydney, NSW|date=2005|pages=31|url=http://www.mca.com.au/general/FINAL_2005_Annual_Report.pdf|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref> and is a member of the Museum's Artists Board.<ref name="Viscopy09">{{cite web|url=http://www.viscopy.org.au/board|title=VISCOPY <U+2013> Board and Directors|publisher=VISCOPY|accessdate=16 February 2010}}</ref> She is on the board of the Indigenous training organisation, Tranby Aboriginal College.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tranby.edu.au/index.php?page=board-of-directors|title=Board of Directors|work=Organisational structure|publisher=Tranby Aboriginal College|accessdate=15 February 2010}}</ref>

Within and beyond her artistic works, Bancroft has demonstrated concern for a range of social issues, particularly those affecting Indigenous Australians. Her painting ''Prevention of AIDS'' (1992) was reproduced on posters and postcards aimed at raising awareness of [[HIV/AIDS in Australia|HIV/AIDS]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Sendziuk|first=Paul|title=Learning to Trust: Australian responses to AIDS|publisher=University of New South Wales Press|location=Sydney|date=2003|page=207|isbn=0868407186}}</ref> and was one of several of her images commissioned by the Commonwealth's [[Department of Health and Ageing|Department of Health]] to highlight issues regarding HIV/AIDS in the Indigenous community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080709202332/www.bronwynbancroft.com/4.html|title=Past Exhibitions|last=Bancroft|first=Bronwyn|work=Designer Aboriginals|accessdate=13 November 2009}}</ref> In 2000, two years after the death of activist [[Mum (Shirl) Smith]], Bancroft and the Boomalli Aboriginal Artists Co-operative organised a fund-raising exhibition of art works in Smith's honour.<ref>{{cite news|title=Strong but fair, the Redfern reformer who didn't cop it|last=Jopson|first=Debra|date=22 November 2000|work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>

Bancroft is a director of the Australian Indigenous Mentoring Experience, a not-for-profit organisation that aims to increase senior high school and university admission rates for Indigenous students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aimementoring.com/about.htm|title=What is AIME mentoring?|date=2009|publisher=Australian Indigenous Mentoring Experience|accessdate=8 October 2009}}</ref> She has taught and mentored Indigenous school students such as Jessica Birk, a winner of the [[Australia Council for the Arts|Australia Council]]'s inaugural Emerging and Young Artist Award in May 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Artist stands astride two worlds|last=Schwartzkoff|first=Louise|date=27 May 2009|work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>

